ARTICLE 2 OWNERSHIP AND USE OF SHARED FACILITIES 2.1 Construction and Ownership of Shared Facilities. (a) The Owners have entered into (or will enter into) the Shared Facilities Construction Subcontract with the Subcontractor, pursuant to which the Subcontractor shall install the Shared Facilities in accordance with the Plans. 30010\5995435.3 9 4836-7695-1708.3 (b) Pursuant to the Shared Facilities Construction Subcontract, upon the earlier of the date each component of the Shared Facilities is delivered to the Shared Facilities Area or incorporated into the Shared Facilities, an undivided tenancy in common ownership percentage interest in such component of the Shared Facilities shall pass to each Owner from the Subcontractor in an amount equal to the Shared Facilities Ownership Percentage for such Owner set forth on Schedule 2.1.
(c) Notwithstanding the transfer of title to the Shared Facilities described above, pursuant to the Shared Facilities Construction Subcontract, the Subcontractor shall retain the risk of loss, care, custody, and control of all Shared Facilities equipment, hardware and materials delivered to Subcontractor and shall exercise due care with respect thereto until the date on which Facility Substantial Completion (as defined in the Shared Facilities Construction Subcontract) occurs, at which time the Owners shall take possession and control thereof and risk of loss therefor.
(d) The Shared Facilities Ownership Percentage of each Owner on Schedule 2.1 (and each Owner???s corresponding Maximum Capacity set forth on Schedule 1.1) shall be amended effective as of the effective date of any Owner assignments of all or any portion of their Shared Facilities Ownership Percentages as permitted in this Agreement and the Administrative Manager shall distribute revised Schedule(s) to each Owner promptly thereafter reflecting such amendments. (e) The ownership structure set forth in this Section 2.1 is not organized with the intention or expectation of producing revenue or making a profit from the operation of the Shared Facilities but merely as an ownership form through which the Owners can accomplish their purpose of owning, operating and making the Shared Facilities available for the use of the Owners in connection with their respective, separate Projects. Nothing in this Agreement is intended or shall be construed to create any partnership, joint venture or similar relationship between the Owners; and in no event shall any Owner take a position on any tax return or other writing of any kind that a partnership, joint venture or other similar relationship exists. The Owners do not intend to form or hold themselves out as a de jure or defacto partnership, joint venture or similar relationship, to share profits or losses, or to share any joint control over financial decisions or discretionary actions (other than as may be expressly provided herein or the Land Rights Documents). At no time shall the Shared Facilities be used by any person other than an Operating Owner, except as otherwise may be required by Applicable Law. Subject to the rights of each Owner under Article 7, in the event of the possible sale or other disposition of all or a portion of its ownership interest in the Shared Facilities, or under Section 12.4 in the event all or a portion of the Shared Facilities is or are removed from service, the Owners do not expect to receive any material amount of revenue from the Shared Facilities. 2.2 Use of Shared Facilities, Separate Facilities in Shared Facilities Area, Curtailment. (a) Interconnection, Maximum Capacity and Other Use Right Provisions.
Subject to the terms and provisions of this Agreement, applicable Governmental Approvals and the applicable Owner???s Interconnection Agreement, once the installation of the Shared Facilities is completed, each Operating Owner shall have the right to utilize the Shared Facilities and the 30010\5995435.3 10 4836-7695-1708.3 Shared Facilities Area (together with other facilities in which such Owner holds an interest) to interconnect its Project and to deliver electrical energy generated by its Project up to such Operating Owner???s Maximum Capacity at the Point of Interconnection. Substantially concurrently with the installation of the Shared Facilities, each of Cove 1 and Cove 2 is having certain separately owned interconnection facilities (e.g. 34.5kV bus, feeder breaker and disconnect facilities, step-up transformer, feeder protection systems, capacitor banks, metering equipment, panels in the MEER, a SCADA network equipment and other interconnection related facilities to be utilized solely by each such Owner???s project) installed in the Shared Facilities Area by the Subcontractor in accordance with the Plans that will facilitate each Owner???s ability to utilize the Shared Facilities (together with other facilities in which such Owner holds an interest) to interconnect its Project and to deliver electrical energy generated by its Project up to such Project???s Maximum Capacity at the Point of Interconnection. No Owner shall interconnect with the Shared Facilities electric generation facilities with an aggregate capacity (net of line losses arising prior to the Point of Interconnection) that exceeds such Owner???s Maximum Capacity at the Point of Interconnection. Cove Mountain Solar, LLC
Market-Based Rate Wholesale Power Sale Tariff
1. Availability. Cove Mountain Solar, LLC ("Seller") makes electric energy, capacity, and ancillary services available under this Tariff to any purchaser for resale. 2. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all sales of capacity, energy, or ancillary services by Seller not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule. 3. Rates. All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 4. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions of sales shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 5. Ancillary Services. Seller may make available to any purchaser the following ancillary services. a. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. b. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. c. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. d. PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. e. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (???MISO???) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. f. Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (???SPP???) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. g. Third Party Provider: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider???s OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 6. Compliance with Commission Regulations. Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff. 7. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority. Seller has received (i) waiver of the accounting and reporting requirements contained in 18 C.F.R. Parts 41, 101 (with the exception that waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licensees is not granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects), and 141, except for Section 141.15; (ii) waiver of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subparts B and C, except for Sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15, and 35.16; and (iii) blanket authorization under 18 C.F.R. Part 34 of all future issuances of securities and assumption of liabilities. See Cove Mountain Solar, LLC, Docket No. ER20-1014-000 (2020). Seller???s tariff excludes market-based sales to customers located within the Puget Sound Energy Balancing Authority Area. See Puget Sound Energy, Inc., 181 FERC ?? 61,008 (2022). 8. Mitigated Sales. Sales of energy and capacity are permissible under this tariff in all balancing authority areas where the Seller has been granted market-based rate authority. Sales of energy and capacity under this tariff are also permissible at the metered boundary between the Seller's mitigated balancing authority area and a balancing authority area where the Seller has been granted market-based rate authority provided: (i) legal title of the power sold transfers at the metered boundary of the balancing authority area where the seller has market-based rate authority; and (ii) if the Seller sells at the metered boundary of a mitigated balancing authority area at market-based rates, then neither it nor its affiliates can sell into that mitigated balancing authority area from the outside. Seller must retain, for a period of five years from the date of the sale, all data and information related to the sale that demonstrates compliance with items (i) and (ii) above. 9. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 1 seller in the Central, Northeast, Southeast, Southwest, and Southwest Power Pool regions, as defined by 18 C.F.R. ?? 35.36(a). Seller is a Category 2 seller in the Northwest region, as defined by 18 C.F.R. ?? 35.36(a).
